–1400":"1340–1400","1268–Female":"1268–Deceased","1275–1374":"1275–1374","1175–1238":"1175–1238","1176–1283":"1176–1283","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1176":"1176","1374":"1374","1175":"1175","1340":"1340","1230":"1230","1283":"1283","1238":"1238","1268":"1268","1400":"1400","1300":"1300","1266":"1266","about 1268":"about 1268","1219":"1219","Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland":"Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom",", , , Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Lag Castle Cemetery Dumfries, Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland":"Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland":"Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"MacGregor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish:  see  McGregor  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McGregor","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Griogair</b> or <b>Mac Greagair</b> ‘son of <i>Griogar</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name   Gregory  . Compare   Grierson  .","History: The Scottish Highland clan McGregor claims descent from the king of Picts and Scots Kenneth MacAlpin (Cináed mac Ailpín; 810–858  AD ). The origins of the clan are unclear. In the 13th century it was established on lands on the shores of Loch Awe and already in conflict with its neighbors of Clan Campbell. By the 16th century the McGregors had retreated deep into Glen Strae and acquired the nickname ‘Children of the Mist’. In 1603 the clan was abolished by royal edict and many members of the clan changed their surname. A year later, the chief of Clan McGregor and eleven of his followers were hanged in Edinburgh. Despite the proscription, the clan survived and supported the king in the Scottish Civil War (1644–51). The exploits of the Jacobite leader Rob Roy McGregor (1671–1734) were romanticized in a novel by Sir Walter Scott. The proscription was eventually repealed in 1774."]}]},{"name":"Gregor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of <b>Gregory</b> ; in part an Anglicized form of Gaelic   Griogair  , which gave rise to the Highland surname <i>MacGregor</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Gregory","meanings":["Via Latin <i>Gregorius</i> from the post-classical Greek name <i>Gregōrios</i> ‘watchful’ (a derivative of <i>gregōrein</i> ‘to watch, be vigilant’). The name was a very popular one among the early Christians, who were mindful of the injunction ‘be sober, be vigilant’ (1 Peter 5:8). It was borne by a number of early saints. The most important, in honour of whom the name was often bestowed from medieval times onwards, were Gregory of Nazianzen (  <i>c.</i>329–90 ), Gregory of Nyssa (  d. <i>c.</i>395 ), Gregory of Tours (  538–94 ), and  Pope Gregory the Great  (  <i>c.</i>540–604 ). A famous bearer of the name in modern times is the film star  Gregory Peck  (  1916–2003 ). The name has traditionally been popular in Scotland, where it is often found in the form  <b>Gregor</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lord Gregor MacGregor 10th Lord Lag, MacGregor was born in 1220, in Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland, his father, William MacGregor of Glenorchy, was 45 and his mother, Margaret de Lindsay, was 45. He married Lady Marion de Lennox MacGregor in 1266, in Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in 1300, in Glenorchy, Argyll, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 80, and was buried in Dumfries, Dumfriesshire, Scotland."},"et":{"1220–1300":"1220–1300","1230–1300":"1230–1300","1340–1400":"1340–1400","1268–Female":"1268–Surnud","1275–1374":"1275–1374","1175–1238":"1175–1238","1176–1283":"1176–1283","1220":"1220","1275":"1275","1176":"1176","1374":"1374","1175":"1175","1340":"1340","1230":"1230","1283":"1283","1238":"1238","1268":"1268","1400":"1400","1300":"1300","1266":"1266","about 1268":"umbes 1268","1219":"1219","Glenorchy, Argyll, S